[Outbreaks continue in a significant number of states. Kentucky, by far, leads the pack.

Except for Arizona, all the other state data is obtained via the CDC website https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/outbreaks/2017March-HepatitisA.htm. Outbreaks in California and Utah have been declared over.

Arkansas https://www.healthy.arkansas.gov/programs-services/topics/hepatitis-a:
As of 3 Jan 2019
The ADH is responding to an outbreak in northeast Arkansas. Since February 2018, 335 cases have been reported as part of this outbreak.

Arizona https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona-health/2019/04/30/what-you-need-know-arizonas-hepatitis-outbreak-maricopa-pima-county/3551069002/:
So far in 2019, there have been 212 cases reported in Arizona, which is higher than any yearly statewide total in more than a decade, state data shows, and state health officials expect that number to rise.

Colorado https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vSrN6YvR6zibn7hg7g78DpjhpQYEZR3H7H34_Pl1As8Uo237X82NmRRxdpscSyNuJ6gWIKyFBWt7pG3/pub:
As of 8 May 2019, there have been 57 cases, 33 hospitalizations, 0 deaths.

Florida http://www.floridahealth.gov/diseases-and-conditions/vaccine-preventable-disease/hepatitis-a/surveillance-data/index.html:
From 1 Jan 2018 through 4 May 2019, 1585 hepatitis A cases were reported. The number of reported hepatitis A cases more than doubled from 2016 to 2017 and nearly doubled again in 2018 after remaining relatively stable in previous years. Case counts in 2019 have already surpassed those in 2018.

Georgia https://dph.georgia.gov/sites/dph.georgia.gov/files/related_files/site_page/Hepatitis%20A%20Advisory_March%202019_final.pdf:
11 Mar 2019
Since January 2018, the Georgia Department of Public Health (DPH) has identified 170 acute hepatitis A virus (HAV) infections statewide (to date), more than 6 times higher than the total of 24 infections identified in 2017. Nearly 60% of the infections have occurred in northwest and north Georgia as well as the Augusta area. HAV infections are continuing to increase in all 3 of these districts, indicative of an HAV outbreak. Increases have also been seen in other areas of the state and are being monitored closely.

